<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="1">
The weakly electric Neotropical fish genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
has been the subject of several taxonomic studies in recent years (Mago-Leccia 1994; Albert &amp; Miller 1995; Campos da Paz 1996; Campos da Paz &amp; Costa 1996; Albert et al. 1999; Campos da Paz 2000; Albert 2001; Albert &amp; Crampton 2001; Campos da Paz 2002). Until recently 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
was recognized as the only genus in the family Gymnotidae. The monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:49CB3AFB-2B08-424B-B3F9-F721357C8702" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Electrophorus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Electrophorus Gill 1864:151" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Electrophorus Gill</taxonomicName>
, comprising the single strongly electric species 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Electrophorus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="electricus">Electrophorus electricus (L.)</taxonomicName>
was recently included in the Gymnotidae (Albert 2001).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="3" pageNumber="2">
Albert (2001) and Albert and Crampton (2001) summarized the diagnostic characters of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
. Albert and Miller (1995) and Albert (2001) recognized three species groups within the genus based on color pattern, body proportions and counts. These are the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C49F8B13-DE26-4766-BDA0-3B44A5D64C80" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus cylindricus La Monte 1935:2" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cylindricus">G. cylindricus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pantherinus">G. pantherinus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
species-groups. The species composition and geographical range of these groups are summarized in Table 1. The 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C49F8B13-DE26-4766-BDA0-3B44A5D64C80" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus cylindricus La Monte 1935:2" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cylindricus">G. cylindricus</taxonomicName>
species-group is endemic to both Atlantic and Pacific drainages of Middle America and comprises just two species. The 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
species-group is endemic to South America and is represented by seven species distributed from the Pacific slope of Colombia to the Pampas of Argentina. The 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pantherinus">G. pantherinus</taxonomicName>
species-group is represented by nine species with distributions from Panama to Paraguay. Species in the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
species-group, including the new species described here, can be distinguished from species in the 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pantherinus">G. pantherinus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C49F8B13-DE26-4766-BDA0-3B44A5D64C80" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus cylindricus La Monte 1935:2" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cylindricus">G. cylindricus</taxonomicName>
species-groups by the possession of a clear or pale patch near the caudal end of the anal fin, and two (vs. one) laterosensory canal pores in the preopercular-mandibular series of the dorso-posterior portion of the preopercle. We use the above classification of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
as a basis for the differential diagnosis of the new species described in this report. There are currently 18 valid species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
, of which thirteen are found in the Amazon basin. Several new species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
have recently been discovered in the Brazilian portion of the Amazon basin (Albert &amp; Crampton 2001; Campos da Paz 2002), including seven new species from whitewater floodplains or ‘ 
<normalizedToken originalValue="várzeas">varzeas</normalizedToken>
’ along the Amazon River’s main stem (Albert &amp; Crampton 2001). Here we describe a new species from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="várzea">varzea</normalizedToken>
floodplains of the Rio Ucayali Basin in the Peruvian Amazon.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
